{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A file placed inside a subdirectory of the watched root is processed, not only files placed directly in the root directory.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Recursive watch behavior is often determined by the real watcher+OS event stack. A mock watcher can emit idealized nested events and miss real failures (e.g., recursion not enabled/supported).","test_description":"Start the daemon against a real temporary directory tree on disk. Create `root/sub/a.txt` after startup, wait for pipeline completion, and assert transformed output appears in the output directory exactly once. Use the actual watch mechanism used in production.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The deduplication logic correctly discards a second processing request for the same file path within a configurable time window.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Core risk is interaction between dedup cache/windowing and processing trigger flow. A pure unit test of a helper can miss path normalization, clock wiring, or queue integration bugs.","test_description":"Wire real dedup + scheduler/queue modules (no OS watcher required). Submit two requests for the same canonical path within the configured window and assert only one pipeline execution occurs; submit again after the window and assert it executes once more.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the operating system emits multiple filesystem events for a single file write, the daemon processes the file exactly once.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This failure boundary is the real filesystem event stream; duplicate event patterns vary by OS/filesystem/watcher backend. Mocking events can hide the production duplicate pattern.","test_description":"Run daemon with a real watched directory. Perform a write pattern known to generate multiple events (create + append + rename or chunked writes). Assert exactly one completed transform/output for that file path.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.13,"System":0.85,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"If the watched directory is removed and then recreated while the daemon is running, the daemon resumes watching the new directory without a restart.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Directory deletion/recreation semantics and watch reattachment are OS-level behaviors. In-process mocks usually do not reproduce watcher invalidation and re-subscription edge cases.","test_description":"Start daemon watching a real directory. Delete the watched directory, recreate it at the same path, then create a new file in the recreated directory. Assert the new file is processed without restarting the daemon.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.95,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When multiple files arrive at the same time, they are processed in the order determined by their creation timestamps.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Ordering depends on real timestamp metadata, filesystem granularity, and concurrent event arrival timing. Mocked metadata can mask ties/precision/race behavior seen in production.","test_description":"Create multiple files near-simultaneously in a real watched directory with controlled creation timing, capture processing order from daemon logs/trace hook, and assert it matches sorted creation timestamps (including deterministic tie-break rule if timestamps are equal).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A file that is still being written to when the arrival event fires is not picked up for processing until writing is complete.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Correctness depends on real write-in-progress behavior (partial content visibility, event timing, stabilization checks). Mocking write completion can make this always pass.","test_description":"With daemon running, open a file in the watched directory and write it in chunks with delays. Verify processing does not start after the first chunk/event, then completes only after final chunk/close (or after configured stability window), and output reflects full content.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.13,"System":0.85,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
